acrifi cial system, the construction of the Temple, and the making of priestly garments, the Mishneh Torah represents Maimonides’ conception of Judaism. Maimonides held that the version of Judaism believed in and practiced by many pious Jews of his generation had been infected with pagan notions. In the Mishneh Torah, he aimed at cleansing Judaism from these non-Jewish practices and beliefs and impressing upon readers that Jewish law and ritual are free from irrational and superstitious practices. Without Red Strings or Holy Water explores Maimonides’ views regarding God, the commandments, astrology, medicine, the evil eye, amulets, magic, theurgic practices, omens, communicating with the dead, the messianic era, midrashic literature, and the oral law. Without Red Strings or Holy Water will be of interest to all who are interested in the intellectual history of Judaism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aRELIGION / Judaism / Sacred Writings.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2013z978311102408008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2015z978311068814608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertReligious Studies ASPz97831107168320 cprintz978193623548340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978161811090940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781618110909423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781618110909/original  a978-3-11-068814-6  Academic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2015c2008d2015  a978-3-11-071683-2  Religious Studies ASP  a978-3-11-102408-0  Academic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2013c2008d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aE